Jun 28 2009	Incredible value in the heart of San Francisco	After many weeks of researching for nice and convenient place to stay, Comfort Inn By the Bay garnered most appeal to me due to favorable feedback it received with regard to location, service quality and the vast range of offered amenities. Having stayed 2 nights at this hotel I really found it to be a delightful facility perfectly suited for those looking to do some productive sightseeing or many other tourist activities. While this is far from a luxury accommodation and certain aspects of this hotel's interior do show their age, I would be at fault in my review not to highlight those attributes that made this Comfort Inn for me truly stand out among its many neighboring competitors. Being one of the only high rise constructions in its vicinity Comfort Inn By the Bay should take special pride in allowing many of its guests enjoy truly beautiful views of one of San Francisco's most iconic landmarks, The Golden Gate Bridge, just outside the window of most of its upper floor rooms. The view is truly nothing short of spectacular and is guaranteed to keep you glued to the window giving you immediate inspiration on some nice compositions for your first pictures of the San Francisco Bay. That first image of the Golden Gate Bridge, a marvel of 20th century engineering achievements and full of fascinating history, will stay with you long after you leave. To hotel's another credit it is conveniently located at one of the centerpiece intersections of San Francisco, the corner of Van Ness Avenue and Lombard Street. This corner can get busy with car and pedestrian traffic, but it is neither overbearing nor particularly noisy for hotel guests inside the room due to a solid soundproof window construction. However, it is really the close proximity to major San Francisco landmarks which greatly benefits Comfort Inn by the Bay and hence helps seal the deal for a casual tourist looking to be within walking distance to many popular establishments. From the historic Ghirardelli Square with its vibrant shopping scene on the north-eastern side of the hotel to the colorful and upbeat ambience of Fisherman's Wharf area a bit further down with plenty of activity near a waterfront on the stretch of adjoining piers, you've got it all within a mere 10-20 minute walk from hotel's entrance. A pleasant walk to the north-west, in 20-25 minutes will get you to the beautiful Palace of Fine Arts and a green mile closer to exploring the grandeur of Golden Gate Bridge itself. And of course the mesmerizing San Francisco landscape renowned for its unusually steep slopes wouldn't be complete without a celebrated &quot;crookedest&quot; region of the Lombard Street, which is literally just 3 blocks directly east of Comfort Inn by the Bay.I felt that the service provided by this facility was quite admirable given the scale and class of the hotel. Even though my request for an early check-in was not immediately fulfilled upon arrival (I specifically requested it well in advance), I observed that concierge personnel acted with utmost professionalism in resolving this oversight and within 20 minutes I was already enjoying a gorgeous scenery of San Francisco Bay from the comfort of my upper floor room window. The size of the room was adequate, the furnishings a bit dated though well maintained; but more importantly the bed mattresses were notably comfortable and floors utterly clean. The extent of various amenities and guest services offered by Comfort Inn by the Bay was another dealbreaker for me as I consider it of great value when my hotel stay includes hassle-free car parking and complimentary breakfast, both of which were conveniently provided here and deserve a good mention. A free breakfast which ran daily from 6:00 - 10:00am may not have been deluxe but was decidedly better than what one would expect from the chain hotel of this kind. The breakfast staff worked hard to replenish yummy pastries, english muffins, white &amp; wheat choice of breads, fresh fruits (both apples and oranges), hard boiled eggs, cereal, oatmeal, coffee, tea, as well as juices (apple and orange). On top of all, you could even indulge in making your own waffles using one of the 2 waffle maker machines available in the breakfast area. I genuinely felt that the quality of service in the breakfast room was splendid, which was yet another example of the distinction the hotel had going for it. Even though my stay fell on the weekend and the hotel was near its maximum capacity from what I heard, I was pleasantly surprised with always being able to get a seat during the breakfast hours on both mornings. San Francisco was my first destination as part of the 10-day long road trip journey along the California coast, Arizona, and Nevada. With this in mind, among all things I was looking for an accommodation with a secured parking facility. The research I conducted showed that hotel parking in San Francisco is generally anything but affordable with average per night rates approaching a $40-$50 range. Comfort Inn by the Bay was no miracle but it yet again managed to impress me by providing a great bargain on parking, only $26/night + tax (around $29.85 total). The parking lot itself consisted of a 3-level underground garage which fundamentally suffered from low clearance and very narrow turning radius. The lack of space here was so severe that moving in and out of your spot as well as navigating from one level to the next in the garage was a strenuous drill. As others have already noted, be extra careful bringing anything larger than a mid-size class vehicle irrespective of your parking skills. The elevator service in the parking garage was running from the upper level only, and I believe there's a 15-minute time limit for parking here intended for simply leaving your car during the check-in procedure. That being said, if you have a lot of luggage I'd suggest to briefly park your car there for unloading purpose and then move it down one or two levels for your final overnight parking. While working out the details of my rental vehicle pickup I heard many locals advise against using a car in San Francisco, so I decided to leave this errand for the last day of my stay here. Admittedly, I was happy to do so as finding a good parking spot on the streets of San Francisco is exceedingly difficult and time consuming. I paid particular attention to street parking in the course of sightseeing and could hardly ever spot a vacant parking space even one managed by a meter. If you do already have a car with you I would still strongly advise to leave it behind in hotel's garage and use the city's excellent public transportation system that includes buses, trolleys, metro, street cars, and world famous cable cars to get around.By virtue of such distinct range of benefits provided by Comfort Inn by the Bay I managed to accomplish an abundance of tourist activities all in just under 2 days. I started out with Mr. Toad's 3-hour &quot;Postcard San Francisco&quot; tour early afternoon followed by a relaxing stroll along Fisherman's Wharf district, which still allowed for plenty of time to capture spectacular shots of this beautiful city, even for most zealous photographer. On to a 2nd day of my stay, it wouldn't really be a trip to San Francisco have I not boarded one of many Bay cruises to take me along world famous San Francisco Bay including a short but memorable swing under the magnificent Golden Gate Bridge itself. Among the many thrills I had in San Francisco another one that stood out was a cable car ride along the Powell-Mason line, which again was made easily possible for its close proximity to Comfort Inn by the Bay. From one end of the line to the other was a convenient 15-minute ride, which brought me into the heart of San Francisco's Union Square district known for its snappy ambience and diverse shopping scene. Genuine lovers of zesty city life and high profile businesses and shopping centers will find plenty to do here. I then decided to round up my city transit experience by getting a taste of San Francisco metro and trolley, both of which were cheap and efficient in helping me get back to the hotel. As the day slowly began its retreat I took my rental up for a leisurely drive over Golden Gate Bridge to the charming town of Sausalito for some truly remarkable scenery and a delicious dinner at &quot;Horizons&quot;. Watching the sun set around San Francisco Bay from the restaurant deck here at Sausalito and gazing at seagulls making their rounds from here to Angel Island and further down to Alcatraz was absolutely breathtaking making it for a perfect way to wrap up my visit to this ravishing part of the world. As the first destination on my road trip along the southwestern U.S., San Francisco left me dazzled and incredibly inspired. I owe it to Comfort Inn by the Bay for helping me effectively materialize all of my ambitions while exploring the city of such scope and charm. The impressions here were plenty but I'm convinced they are still among very few yet to be surpassed.	
